 true` if `opts.LocalDev` is true, and never sets it to false. The old code used `settings.LocalDev = localDev` which unconditionally synced. Now if the user runs `entire enable --local-dev` and later runs `entire enable` (without the flag), the setting remains `true`.\\n\\nHowever, I think this is actually by design. The pattern `if opts.X { settings.X = true }` means \\\"only turn it on if explicitly requested\\\". But the Bugbot is pointing out that `EnsureSetup()` and `setupGitHook()` read from settings later, which could reinstall hooks with the stale configuration.\\n\\nActually, looking more carefully:\\n- The hooks are installed using `opts` values (lines 231-234, 632-635)\\n\\n\\n- But `EnsureSetup()` (called later at line 253, 653) uses settings via `settings.Load()`\\n- Similarly, `setupGitHook()` (line 726-735) loads from settings\\n\\nSo there's an inconsistency: initial hook installation uses `opts` values while later calls use `settings` values. The fix should ensure that after updating settings with opts values, we use the settings values for hook installation to maintain consistency between what's saved and what's installed.\\n\\nIn `runEnableInteractive` after line 195, I should switch to reading from settings when installing hooks:\\n\\n```go\\nif _, err := strategy.InstallGitHook(true, settings.LocalDev, settings.AbsoluteGitHookPath); err != nil {\\n    return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to install git hooks: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\nstrategy.CheckAndWarnHookManagers(w, settings.LocalDev, settings.AbsoluteGitHookPath)\\n```\\n\\nApply the same change to `setupAgentHooksNonInteractive`. This way, whether the flag is passed or the setting already exists, the hooks get installed with whatever state is currently in settings, which represents the merged configuration.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":8,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":16160,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":35309,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemer